The index has been steadily growing since november 2020 with only a slight decrease in june and july and it is at 134.4 for november 2021 (https://www.fao.org/worldfoodsituation/foodpricesindex/en/). The historical (1990-2020) average MoM change november-december has been -0.27% and for the last decade -0.15%. If you take the greatest decrease in the same period of -3.99% (2008) the index could go down to 129.03. For the index to go down to 130.0 the index had to go down -3.27%. The historical probability for this given the MoM changes since 1990 is of 7.13%. Therefore At this point I am assigning a 93% probability for more than 130.0 and 7% for between 120.0 and 130.0.

With the June print of 124.6, we have the first decrease after 12 consecutive months of increases... largely powered by a 10% drop in vegetable oil prices (which had nearly doubled in price). I'm interpreting this as a sign that producers have increased supply in response to the profit opportunities, and vegetable oil prices are unlikely to regain their constantly increasing trend.

It looks like pandemic dislocations are finally starting to resolve. The index went down to 124.6 in the latest report, largely because of a huge, nearly 10% drop in vegetable oil prices, which are finally coming down. Everything else pretty much canceled out. Cereals and dairy went down, by 2.6% and 1.0%, respectively. Meat and sugar went up, by 2.1% and 0.9%, respectively. It's conceivable prices could be even lower by Dec., if cereals crops and the oil production/consumption balance are as good as forecast. I'm still not as sanguine about cereals production forecasts as the futures markets are currently, but realistically, production will probably be very good. And if cereals can keep falling or at least stay stable, so should meat and dairy, to a large extent. So I'm shifting my forecast downward. 6 months left to go. It's not unreasonable to think we could end up back where the price index was around Oct. or Nov. 2020, just over 100. I am still trying to force myself to spread out my forecasts over more bins. I haven't done that very well on this question so far. Trying to improve.

Update. The index rose again for March, led by an 8% increase in vegetable oil prices, followed by dairy at 4% and meat at 2%. Sugar prices fell by 4%, and cereals fell by 2%. Bumper cereal crops are expected in 2021, but demand for cereals is expected to overtake production, thanks to increasing feed use. "World cereal stocks at the end of 2021 are forecast to decline by 1.7 percent from their opening levels to 808 million tonnes. Combined with the utilization forecasts, the global cereal stock-to-use ratio for 2020/21 is foreseen to dip to a seven-year low of 28.4 percent." https://reliefweb.int/report/world/global-food-prices-rise-10th-month-row

The FAO Food Price Index (FFPI) averaged 118.5 points in March 2021, 2.4 points (2.1 percent) higher than in February. The increase marked the tenth consecutive monthly rise in the value of the FFPI to its highest level since June 2014. The FAO Cereal Price Index averaged 123.6 points in March, down 2.2 points (1.7 percent) from February, ending the eight-month rising trend, but still 25.9 points (26.5 percent) above its March 2020 level. Among major cereals, wheat export prices declined the most in March, falling 2.4 percent, however, they remained 19.5 percent higher than in the same month last year. The FAO Dairy Price Index averaged 117.4 points in March, up 4.4 points (3.9 percent) from February, rising for the tenth consecutive month and lifting the index to nearly 16 percent above its value in the corresponding month last year. The FAO Meat Price Index* averaged 98.9 points in March, up 2.2 points (2.3 percent) from February, continuing the upward trend for the sixth consecutive month, but still stood slightly (0.5 percent) below its value a year ago. Poultry and pig meat quotations increased, underpinned by a fast pace of imports by Asian countries, mainly China. A surge in internal sales in Europe in preparation for the Easter celebrations also supported pig meat prices. The FAO Sugar Price Index averaged 96.2 points in March, down 4 points (4.0 percent) from February, marking the first decline after sharp increases registered in the previous two months. Sugar quotations remained, however, more than 30 percent above their levels in the corresponding period of last year, underpinned by concerns over tight global supplies in 2020/21. http://www.fao.org/worldfoodsituation/foodpricesindex/en/

Just like @Pedro-Goncalves my first attempt to figure out how the index works. If you look at the history of the index it spend most of its time below 100, food prices where falling in most years. (1) The biggest problem this year will probably be logistics, not enough (refrigerated) containers available to ship food to markets or shipping prices to high to make it profitable shipping (bulky) foodstuff. (2) This was also the reason the index rose in 2020.

Comment: It is my first attempt to see how it works, I have to do some more research on the topic to improve prediction. Rationale: the pandemic, abnormal weather events for the season, some political and economic instability in countries that produce food, slow vaccination campaigns, no new technologies to increase production to balance a weather related disruption (that I know of), governments will try to attenuate the problem, investment in automation is possible and could keep the index from getting out of control (international cooperation could be necessary though).

Looking at historical data, 100-110 and 110-120 seem most likely bets given where it is now. My general sense of the underlying fundamentals, including pandemic disruptions, inflationary pressures due to government spending, and continued global political turmoil, it does seem there are significant upward pressures. The index spends very little time over 130, so, this far out, I see that as unlikely on the date picked, but maybe not unlikely at some point in the next year.

The FAO Food Price Index averaged 116.0 in February, 2021 and has risen for the past 9 months, by an average of about 3.6 points per month, and 2.8 points from Jan. to Feb. 2021. Some portion of this meteoric rise can be attributed to pandemic disruptions, but a wide range of unrelated and correlated factors are contributing significantly as well, from weather to speculative investment to politics. I don't see an end in 2021 to the forces propelling the index upward, but this index can be quite volatile.

There seems to have been crop failures in some regions of the world, in some places maybe driven by drought and heat waves, in other places, probably in Eastern Africa, mostly driven by mass locust appearance. This is what the onset of the current price rally in September 2020, and the sharp price increase in mainly Cereals and Vegetable oils suggest. These two likely also have the heaviest weight in the basket of five subsegments. All other segments have increased only moderately and are still below the average of 116.0 as of Feb 2021. Going back in history, 2008/09 and 2011/12 appear to be an apt comparison to 2020/21, and in both cases, one year of sharp price increases, driven mainly by cereals and vegetable oils, was followed by a year in which the FFPI dropped either sharply (2009) or moderately (2012). While Sugar was a third sector with drastic price changes in both of these cases, it does not play a role this year obviously, as world supply for export from the Northern hemisphere could be sufficient. My guess is prices will continue to rise in H12021, before they drop moderately in H22021 with the harvest in the Northern hemispere (e.g. wheat production in Russia largely determines the world export price for wheat) towards the end of the year. Forecast: above, but near 100.0, maybe 102.5

The Feb. 2021 most recently reported FAO Food Price index value was 116.0, the highest number since 2015. The index value has now increased 16.7 percent since Feb. 2020. (http://www.fao.org/worldfoodsituation/foodpricesindex/en/)

According to the FAO link it's currently at 116 and rising, prior to the pandemic really kicking off in February 2020 it had fallen to the mid 90s. I'm assuming the recent rise is mostly pandemic related. Also I think the rest of the world is a ways off from being out of the woods as far as the pandemic goes, even though the US and other rich countries look like they should be seeing better days this summer due to vaccinations. So I think there's a good chance the index continues to rise through 2021. However, the US sounds like it's one of the larger food producers, so if the US can get its economy back to a relative normal this summer maybe it can bring food prices back down a bit which might keep the FAO index from rising so much. But an increase in inflation could also cause prices to rise more. Based on those considerations I'm putting the most weight on it increasing into the 120s or higher, though setting a decent amount of weight on it staying about the same or coming back down.
